response variable = monocytes (count, discrete) predictor variables = hdl_cholesterol (count, discrete), age (count, continuous) confounding variable = sex (categorical) random variable = cohort (categorical)

hist(df$hdl_cholesterol) #right-skewed

hist(log(df$hdl_cholesterol)) #looks better

shapiro.test(log(df$hdl_cholesterol)) #normalised
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  log(df$hdl_cholesterol)
## W = 0.99602, p-value = 0.9489

Linear Mixed Model Assumptions The explanatory variables are related linearly to the response. (the literature says so) The errors have constant variance. (plot0) The errors are independent. (each observation is independent) The errors are normally distributed. (Q-Q plot)

mod0 <- lme(monocytes ~ log(hdl_cholesterol) + sex, random = ~1|cohort, data = df, method = "ML", na.action = na.omit) 
plot(mod0)  # the errors have constant variance

qqnorm(resid(mod0)) 
qqline(resid(mod0)) # the errors are normally distirbuted

Anova(mod0, type = 2) # monocytes is significantly associated with sex

#Could be a reinforcement interaction effect, the effect of cholesterol on monocytes maybe strengthened by age

#hdl_cholesterol does not seem to predict monocyte count very well; let's exclude it.
mod3 <- lme(monocytes ~ age + sex, random = ~1|cohort, data = df, method = "ML", na.action = na.omit)
plot(mod3)  # the errors have constant variance

qqnorm(resid(mod3)) 
qqline(resid(mod3)) # the errors are even more normally distributed!

Anova(mod3, type = 2) # monocytes is significantly associated with sex and age
## Analysis of Deviance Table (Type II tests)

Conclusion: mod3 is the best model to fit the clinical data.

Sex is a fixed effect as it does not change at a constant rate over time. Sex is a confounding variable (as seen in the previous presentation) and was controlled for. Previous studies have shown postmenopausal women have higher hdl_cholesterol than men of the same age. As such, sex affects both the independent variable (hdl_cholesterol) and the dependent variable.

subjects were placed into cohorts that completed the intervention at different times and places. The creation of cohorts may have lead to “group effects”; this will be accounted for by including the cohort variable as a random effect. Interestingly, cohort only exerts a small random effect onto the model.

#Plot taking into consideration all the variables initially considered
ggplot(data = df, aes(x = log(hdl_cholesterol), y = monocytes, colour = sex)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', se=FALSE) +
  facet_grid(.~agebin) +
  scale_y_continuous(n.breaks = 20) + # make more breaks on the y-axis 
  ylab("Monocytes (frequency in blood)") +
  xlab("HDL_Cholesterol log(mg/dL)") +
  ggtitle("Figure 1: Monocytes vs HDL_Cholesterol")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

#Plot taking into consideration, only the variables that significantly affect monocyte count in the clinical population
df$subject_char <- interaction(df$sex, df$agebin)
ggplot(data = df, aes(x=subject_char, y= monocytes, colour = subject_char)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  theme(axis.ticks = element_blank(), # remove x-axis tick marks
        axis.text.x = element_blank()) + # remove x-axis labels because it is in the legend
  scale_y_continuous(n.breaks = 20) + # make more breaks on the y-axis 
  ylab("Monocytes (frequency in blood)") +
  xlab("") +
  ggtitle("Figure 2: Monocytes vs Subject Characteristics")
